  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These provide frameworks for countries to develop consistent anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n\n2. Legal Harmonization\n- Countries adopt similar legal approaches to defining money laundering\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Consistent mechanisms for identifying and prosecuting financial crimes\n\n3. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigating and prosecuting cross-border money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements for financial criminals\n\n4. Regulatory Compliance\n- Banks and financial institutions must comply with international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information sharing protocols\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International cooperation in tracking and freezing assets\n- Joint investigations\n- Coordinated legal actions against money laundering networks\n\n6. Technological Coordination\n- Shared digital platforms for financial intelligence\n- Cross-border monitoring systems\n- Enhanced digital forensic capabilities\n\nThese intersections create complex but increasingly sophisticated global approaches to combating money laundering.",
